<title>The !khau carried off by a Lion</title>
<summary><i>The !kháü (a Lizard of the Genus Agama) who would not listen to the advice of his wife, and was carried off by a lion. By /han≠kass’o (L VIII.-18. 7626–7638, 20. 7728-7745).</i> The <i>!khau</i> sees the Lion&apos;s &apos;head-shadow&apos; and thinks it is his own. The <i>!khau</i> looks up and sees the Lion, who catches him and eats him.  </summary><comments>1) |han≠kass&apos;o heard this from his mother (|xabbi-an), 2) <i>!khau</i> is sometimes spelt <i>!kau</i> in the stories in which it appears, 3) p.7628v: &apos;Bushman rice&apos; and the maggot&apos;s &apos;houses&apos;, 3) p.7630v: see <i>Lion turns into a man</i>, 4) p.7633v: what people say to different shadows, 5) p.7741v: the name and smell of a plant, 6) This story is found in Book VIII-18 and VIII-20</comments><date>12 October 1878 (started)</date><storypages>7626-7638, 7728-7745</storypages><category>History (Early Race)</category><author>|han≠kass'o (Klein Jantje) (VIII)</author><keyword><kw>lizard</kw><subkw>!kau or !khau</subkw></keyword>
